# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: samoa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Research into this topic is fairly new, with few studies published before 2009, but has gained increasing attention in recent years.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] A cross-sectoral, holistic approach is seen as an important feature of 100% renewable energy systems and is based on the assumption "that the best solutions can be found only if one focuses on the synergies between the sectors" of the energy system such as electricity, heat, transport or industry.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] No uniform definition for 100% renewable energy systems has been adopted across the published literature.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Recent studies show that a global transition to 100% renewable energy across all sectors – power, heat, transport and desalination well before 2050 is feasible.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Existing technologies, including storage, are capable of generating a secure energy supply at every hour throughout the year.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The sustainable energy system is more efficient and cost effective than the existing system.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The United Nations Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) stated in their 2011 report that there is little that limits integrating renewable technologies for satisfying the total global energy demand.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Barriers to implementing the renewable energy plan are seen to be "primarily social and political, not technological or economic".
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson says that energy costs today with a wind, solar, and water system should be similar to today's energy costs from other optimally cost-effective strategies.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The main obstacle against this scenario is the lack of political will.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] His conclusions have been disputed by other researchers.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson published a response that disputed the piece point by point and claimed that the authors were motivated by allegiance to energy technologies that the 2015 paper excluded.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson says that energy costs today with a wind, solar, and water system should be similar to today's energy costs from other optimally cost-effective strategies and he has rebutted their criticisms.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] A followup paper was published by Jacobson and others in 2022, in which paths to 100% renewable energy by 2035 and 2050 were developed for 145 countries.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The study concluded that a wind-water-solar (WWS) based system "requires less energy, costs less, and creates more jobs than business as usual".
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The cost reduction was primarily due to the substantial (-56.4%) decrease in overall energy demand thanks to the increased efficiency of relying on renewable electricity for all energy needs.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2014, renewable sources such as wind, geothermal, solar, biomass, and burnt waste provided 19% of the total energy consumed worldwide, with roughly half of that coming from traditional use of biomass.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The largest sector in terms of energy consumption is electricity with a renewable share of 22.8%, most of it coming from hydropower with a share of 16.6%, followed by wind with 3.1%.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2018, according to REN21, transformation is picking up speed in the power sector, but urgent action is required in heating, cooling and transport.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] There are many places around the world with grids that are run almost exclusively on renewable energy .
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] At the national level, at least 30 nations already have renewable energy contributing more than 20% of the energy supply.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy use has grown more quickly than even advocates anticipated.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2019, however, it needs to grow six times faster to limit global warming to 2 °C (3.6 °F).
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change there are few fundamental technological limits to integrating a portfolio of renewable energy technologies to meet most of total global energy demand.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] 100% renewable energy in a country is typically a more challenging goal than carbon neutrality.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The latter is a climate mitigation target, politically decided by many countries, and may also be achieved by balancing the total carbon footprint of the country (not only emissions from energy and fuel) with carbon dioxide removal and carbon projects abroad.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2018 according to REN21 transformation is picking up speed in the power sector, but urgent action is required in heating, cooling and transport.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] There are many places around the world with grids that are run almost exclusively on renewable energy.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Socolow of Princeton University have developed a series of "climate stabilization wedges" that can allow us to maintain our quality of life while avoiding catastrophic climate change, and "renewable energy sources", in aggregate, constitute the largest number of their "wedges".
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The main barriers to the widespread implementation of large-scale renewable energy and low-carbon energy strategies are political rather than technological.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to the 2013 *Post Carbon Pathways* report, which reviewed many international studies, the key roadblocks are: climate change denial, the fossil fuels lobby, political inaction, unsustainable energy consumption, outdated energy infrastructure, and financial constraints.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Studies have shown that Southeast Asia countries could achieve almost 100% renewable elecitricity based on solar, wind, and off-river pumped hydro energy storage at a competitive LCOE of around US$55–115/MWh.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Using 100% renewable energy was first suggested in a paper in *Science* published in 1975 by Danish physicist Bent Sørensen, which was followed by several other proposals.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 1976, energy policy analyst Amory Lovins coined the term "soft energy path" to describe an alternative future where energy efficiency and appropriate renewable energy sources steadily replace a centralized energy system based on fossil and nuclear fuels.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 1998, the first detailed analysis of scenarios with high shares of renewables were published.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] These were followed by the first detailed 100% scenarios.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2006, a PhD thesis was published by Czisch in which it was shown that in a 100% renewable scenario energy supply could match demand in every hour of the year in Europe and North Africa.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In the same year, Danish Energy professor Henrik Lund published a first paper in which he addresses the optimal combination of renewables, which was followed by several other papers on the transition to 100% renewable energy in Denmark.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Since then, Lund has been publishing several papers on 100% renewable energy.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] After 2009, publications began to rise steeply, covering 100% scenarios for countries in Europe, America, Australia and other parts of the world.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Even in the early 21st century, it was extraordinary for scientists and decision-makers to consider the concept of 100% renewable electricity.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy use has grown much faster than even advocates had anticipated.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Wind turbines generate 39 percent of Danish electricity, and Denmark has many biogas digesters and waste-to-energy plants as well.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Together, wind and biomass provide 44% of the electricity consumed by the country's six million inhabitants.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2010, Portugal's 10 million people produced more than half their electricity from indigenous renewable energy resources.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Spain's 40 million inhabitants meet one-third of their electrical needs from renewables.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy has a history of strong public support.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In America, for example, a 2013 Gallup survey showed that two in three Americans want the U.S. to increase domestic energy production using solar power (76%), wind power (71%), and natural gas (65%).
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Far fewer want more petroleum production (46%) and more nuclear power (37%).
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Least favored is coal, with about one in three Americans favouring it.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Supporters of 100% renewable energy do not consider nuclear power as renewable or sustainable due to perceived risks of disasters and high-level waste management, and consider carbon capture and storage to have limited safe storage potential.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] These constraints have also led to an interest in 100% renewable energy.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] A well established body of academic literature has been written over the past decade, evaluating scenarios for 100% renewable energy for various geographical areas.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In recent years, more detailed analyses have emerged from government and industry sources.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The incentive to use 100% renewable energy is created by global warming and ecological as well as economic concerns, post peak oil.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The first country to propose 100% renewable energy was Iceland, in 1998.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Proposals have been made for Japan in 2003, and for Australia in 2011.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Albania, Iceland, and Paraguay obtain essentially all of their electricity from renewable sources (Albania and Paraguay 100% from hydroelectricity, Iceland 72% hydro and 28% geothermal).
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Norway obtains nearly all of its electricity from renewable sources (97 percent from hydropower).
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Iceland proposed using hydrogen for transportation and its fishing fleet.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Australia proposed biofuel for those elements of transportation not easily converted to electricity.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The road map for the United States, commitment by Denmark, and Vision 2050 for Europe set a 2050 timeline for converting to 100% renewable energy, later reduced to 2040 in 2011.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Zero Carbon Britain 2030 proposes eliminating carbon emissions in Britain by 2030 by transitioning to renewable energy.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2015, Hawaii enacted a law that the Renewable Portfolio Standard shall be 100 percent by 2045.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] This is often confused with renewable energy.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] If electricity produced on the grid is 65 GWh from fossil fuel and 35 GWh from renewable energy and rooftop off grid solar produces 80 GWh of renewable energy, then the total renewable energy is 115 GWh and the total electricity on the grid is 100 GWh.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Cities like Paris and Strasbourg in France, planned to use 100% renewable energy by 2050.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] It is estimated that the world will spend an extra $8 trillion over the next 25 years to prolong the use of non-renewable resources, a cost that would be eliminated by transitioning instead to 100% renewable energy.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Research that has been published in Energy Policy suggests that converting the entire world to 100% renewable energy by 2050 is both possible and affordable, but requires political support.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] It would require building many more wind turbines and solar power systems but wouldn't utilize bioenergy.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Other changes involve use of electric cars and the development of enhanced transmission grids and storage.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] As part of the Paris Agreement, countries periodically update their climate change targets for the future, by 2018 no G20 country had committed to a 100% renewable target.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Until 2018, there were 181 peer-reviewed papers on 100% renewable energy.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In the same year, 100% renewable energy was also mentioned in the Special Report on Global Warming of 1.5 °C as a potential means to "expand the range of 1.5 °C pathways", if the findings can be corroborated.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2021, wind and solar were consistently increasing their share worldwide, but still represented just 5% of global primary energy consumption, albeit far more of useful energy consumption.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Morgan Asset Management (the biggest lender to fossil fuels in the world) analyzed renewable energy forecasts made by eight scientists and research bodies (including Bent Sorensen, Mark Z.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson, Amory Lovins) between 1970 and 2020 and claimed that all of them were unrealistically optimistic as they ignored "energy density, intermittency and the complex realities of incumbent energy systems".
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Some other places have high percentages, for example the electricity sector in Denmark, as of 2014, is 45% wind power, with plans in place to reach 85%.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The electricity sector in Canada and the electricity sector in New Zealand have even higher percentages of renewables (mostly hydro), 65% and 75% respectively, and Austria is approaching 70%.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2015, the electricity sector in Germany sometimes meets almost 100% of the electricity demand with PV and wind power, and renewable electricity is over 25%.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Albania has 94.8% of installed capacity as hydroelectric, 5.2% diesel generator; but Albania imports 39% of its electricity.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2016, Portugal achieved 100% renewable electricity for four days between 7 and 11 May, partly because efficient energy use had reduced electricity demand.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] France and Sweden have low carbon intensity, since they predominantly use a mixture of nuclear power and hydroelectricity.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2018 Scotland met 76% of their demand from renewable sources.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Although electricity is currently around a quarter of world energy supply and consumption; primary energy use is expected to decrease with renewable energy deployment as electricity use increases, as it is likely to be combined with some degree of further electrification.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] For example, electric cars achieve much better fuel efficiency than fossil fuel cars, and another example is renewable heat such as in the case of Denmark, which is proposing to move to greater use of heat pumps for heating buildings to provide multiple kilowatts of heat per kilowatt of electricity.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Other electricity generating sources are considered clean, though not necessarily renewable, as they also do not emit carbon dioxide or other greenhouse gases and air pollutants.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The largest of these is nuclear energy, which produces no emissions.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Some argue that transitioning to 100% renewable energy would be too slow to limit climate change, and that closing down nuclear power stations is a mistake.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Carbon capture and storage projects may still use coal or natural gas but capture carbon dioxide for storage or alternative uses.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Pathways to eliminate greenhouse gases may include these in addition to renewable energy to save money, or to avoid shutting down existing plants and allow for flexibility in designing a carbon-free electric grid.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2018, California passed SB 100, which mandates 100% clean, carbon-free by 2045, including a 60% renewable electricity goal by 2030.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] 2019 legislation in Washington also requires 100% clean electricity by 2045, eliminating coal by 2025.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Further states and territories to require 100% carbon-free electricity are Hawaii, Maine, Minnesota, Nevada, New Mexico, New York, Virginia, Puerto Rico, and Washington, DC.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to a study by Global Energy Monitor, China is expected to generate 1,200 gigawatts of renewable energy (wind and solar) by 2025.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson, the most significant barriers to the widespread implementation of large-scale renewable energy and low carbon energy strategies, at the pace required to prevent runaway climate change, are primarily political and not technological.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] IPCC scenarios "generally indicate that growth in renewable energy will be widespread around the world".
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The IPCC said that if governments were supportive, and the full complement of renewable energy technologies were deployed, renewable energy supply could account for almost 80% of the world's energy use within forty years.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Rajendra Pachauri, chairman of the IPCC, said the necessary investment in renewables would cost only about 1% of global GDP annually.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] This approach could contain greenhouse gas levels to less than 450 parts per million, the safe level beyond which climate change becomes catastrophic and irreversible.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Socolow have developed a series of "climate stabilization wedges" that can allow societies to maintain their quality of life while avoiding catastrophic climate change, and "renewable energy sources", in aggregate, constitute the largest number of their "wedges".
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Brown founder and president of the Earth Policy Institute, a nonprofit research organization based in Washington, D.C., says a rapid transition to 100% renewable energy is both possible and necessary.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Brown compares with the U.S. entry into World War II and the subsequent rapid mobilization and transformation of the US industry and economy.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] A quick transition to 100% renewable energy and saving of our civilization is proposed by Brown to follow an approach with similar urgency.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to World Bank the "below 2°C" climate scenario requires 3 billions of tonnes of metals and minerals by 2050.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Supply of mined resources such as zinc, molybdenum, silver, nickel, copper must increase by up to 500%.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] A 2018 study analysed the metal requirements to transition the global energy system up to 2060.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Currently used battery technologies and known reserves are not compatible with the transition scenario as a result of insufficient cobalt and lithium reserves.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Batteries containing less or no cobalt are feasible.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Lithium is much more difficult to replace with maintained performance and cost.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] A review suggests large institutions are prone to resisting "the challenge of 100% RE scenarios based on the dogma that the world cannot do without fossil fuels and nuclear energy".
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Institutions that have received extensive criticism include the International Energy Agency and the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, with the latter also being criticized for not including studies on 100% RE systems in their IPCC reports.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] A report found that China is about to produce "almost 95% of the world's polysilicon and the ingots and wafers" of the solar panel supply chain, with this level of concentration in any global supply chain "would represent a considerable vulnerability".
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] One of the main obstacles to 100% renewable energy is the intermittency or variability of renewable energy sources – such as times when sufficient amounts of energy can be generated neither via wind nor via solar power ("Dunkelflauten").
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to Amory Lovins the electricity grid alone can compensate for variability, just as it routinely backs up nonworking coal-fired and nuclear plants with working ones.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] For example, it may cost 40% more to reduce carbon emissions without carbon dioxide capture.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The study introduced the term "firm low-carbon energy source" (e.g. nuclear, geothermal), which is intended to operate along "fast-burst" sources (e.g. batteries) and "fuel saving" (VRE).
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] The International Energy Agency says that there has been too much attention on issue of the variability of renewable electricity production.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Variability is rarely a barrier to increased renewable energy deployment when dispatchable generation such as hydroelectricity or solar thermal storage is also available.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] But at high levels of market penetration it requires careful analysis and management, and additional costs may be required for back-up or system modification.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Hydropower is currently the only large scale low-carbon seasonal energy storage.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In countries with high variation in energy demand by season (for example the UK uses far more gas for heating in the winter than it uses electricity) but lacking hydropower electrical interconnectors to countries with lots of hydropower (e.g.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] UK - Norway), electricity from hydropower is likely to be insufficient and development of a hydrogen economy would likely be needed: this is being trialled in the UK and 8 TWh of inter-seasonal hydrogen energy storage has been proposed.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] In Australia, as well as storing renewable energy as hydrogen, it is also proposed to be exported in the form of ammonia.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] McKinsey estimates that it will cost 7.5% of global domestic product between 2021 and 2050 to achieve net zero (not 100% renewable, which will be more expensive).
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Current spending is just over half of this.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] A review identified major gaps and neglected aspects – open research questions – in the 100% RE literature.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] Full decaronization of the energy system by 2050.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p01] 7.16 for renewable target and 12 for national target.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has said that there are few fundamental technological limits to integrating a portfolio of renewable energy technologies to meet most of total global energy demand.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] In a 2011 review of 164 recent scenarios of future renewable energy growth, the report noted that the majority expected renewable sources to supply more than 17% of total energy by 2030, and 27% by 2050; the highest forecast projected 43% supplied by renewables by 2030 and 77% by 2050.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2011, the refereed journal *Energy Policy* published two articles by Mark Z.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] Jacobson, a professor of engineering at Stanford University, and research scientist Mark A.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] Delucchi, about changing the energy supply mix and "Providing all global energy with wind, water, and solar power".
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] The articles analyze the feasibility of providing worldwide energy for electric power, transportation, and heating/cooling from wind, water, and sunlight (WWS), which are safe clean options.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] In Part I, Jacobson and Delucchi discuss WWS energy system characteristics, aspects of energy demand, WWS resource availability, WWS devices needed, and material requirements.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] They estimate that 3,800,000 5 MW wind turbines, 5350 100 MW geothermal power plants, and 270 new 1300 MW hydroelectric power plants would be required.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] In terms of solar power, an additional 49,000 300 MW concentrating solar plants, 40,000 300 MW solar photovoltaic power plants, and 1.7 billion 3 kW rooftop photovoltaic systems would also be needed.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] Such an extensive WWS infrastructure could decrease world power demand by 30%.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] In Part II, Jacobson and Delucchi address variability of supply, system economics, and energy policy initiatives associated with a WWS system.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] The authors advocate producing all new energy with WWS by 2030 and replacing existing energy supply arrangements by 2050.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] Energy costs with a WWS system should be similar to today's energy costs.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] In general, Jacobson has said wind, water and solar technologies can provide 100 percent of the world's energy, eliminating all fossil fuels.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] 0.1% of the time would require generation from other sources.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] In March 2012, Denmark's parliament agreed on a comprehensive new set of promotional programs for energy efficiency and renewable energy aimed at reaching 100 percent of electricity, heat and fuels from renewables by 2050.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] IRENEC is an annual conference on 100% renewable energy started in 2011 by Eurosolar Turkey.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] More recently, Jacobson and his colleagues have developed detailed proposals for switching to 100% renewable energy produced by wind, water and sunlight, for New York, California and Washington states, by 2050.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] As of 2014, a more expansive new plan for the 50 states has been drawn up, which includes an online interactive map showing the renewable resource potential of each of the 50 states.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] The 50-state plan is part of The Solutions Project, an independent outreach effort led by Jacobson, actor Mark Ruffalo, and film director Josh Fox.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] Debate over detailed plans remain, but transformations in global energy services based entirely around renewable energy are in principle technically practicable, economically feasible, socially viable, and so realisable.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] This prospect underpins the ambitious commitment by Germany, one of the world's most successful industrial economies, to undertake a major energy transition, Energiewende.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2015 a study was published in *Energy and Environmental Science* that describes a pathway to 100% renewable energy in the United States by 2050 without using biomass.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] Implementation of this roadmap is regarded as both environmentally and economically feasible and reasonable, as by 2050 it would save about $600 billion of health costs a year due to reduced air pollution and $3.3 trillion global warming costs.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] This would translate in yearly cost savings per head of around $8300 compared to a business as usual pathway.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] According to that study, barriers that could hamper implementation are neither technical nor economic but social and political, as most people didn't know that benefits from such a transformation far exceeded the costs.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] In June 2017, twenty-one researchers published an article in the *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America* rejecting Jacobson's earlier *PNAS* article, accusing him of modeling errors and of using invalid modeling tools.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] They further asserted he made implausible assumptions through his reliance upon increasing national energy storage from 43 minutes to 7 weeks, increasing hydrogen production by 100,000%, and increasing hydropower by the equivalent of 600 Hoover Dams.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] Victor called Jacobson's work "dangerous" and Ken Caldeira emphasized that increasing hydropower output by 1,300 gigawatts, a 25% increase, is the equivalent flow of 100 Mississippi Rivers.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] Jacobson published a response in the same issue of the *PNAS* and also authored a blog post where he asserted the researchers were advocates of the fossil fuel industry.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] Another study published in 2017 confirmed the earlier results for a 100% renewable power system for North America, without changes in hydropower assumptions, but with more realistic emphasis on a balanced storage portfolio, in particular seasonal storage, and for competitive economics.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2015, Jacobson and Delucchi, together with Mary Cameron and Bethany Frew, examined with computer simulation (Loadmatch), in more detail how a wind-water-solar (WWS) system can track the energy demand from minute to minute.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] This turned out to be possible in the United States for 6 years, including WWS variability by extreme weather events.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2017, the plan was further developed for 139 countries by a team of 27 researchers and in 2018, Jacobson and Delucchi with Mary Cameron and Brian Mathiesen published the Loadmatch results for 20 regions in which the 139 countries in the world are divided.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] According to this research, a WWS system can follow the demand in all regions.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] The program has been carried out for each region 10-20 times with adapted input for the storage capacities, until a solution was found in which the energy demand was followed, per half minute for 5 years, with low costs.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2020, Jacobson clarified in a textbook computer simulation results of a WWS energy system.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] To match demand with supply every minute more solar and wind farms and high-voltage lines must be installed than to match year-averaged demand and supply.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] Oversizing (also in a conventional energy system) ensures that the demand can be followed during peak hours, but causes unused supply during off-peak hours.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] In a WWS system, more energy exchange between areas leads to more transmission loss.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] The table shows WWS supply, unused supply, losses and end-use, in GW average power to reliably supply the world and four major regions with energy by 2050.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] See textbook Table 8.10; energy in TWh is divided by 26.3 kh (1000 hours) to get power in GW.
[src:samoa/100-renewable-energy-p02] The bottom row is the storage capacity of pumped hydro plants (Table 8.7).
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] The **1889 Apia cyclone** was a tropical cyclone in the South Pacific Ocean, which swept across Apia, Samoa on March 15, 1889, during the Samoan crisis.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] The effect on shipping in the harbour was devastating, largely because of what has been described as "an error of judgement that will forever remain a paradox in human psychology".
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] Events ashore had led to upheaval in the Pacific nations and colonies.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] Both the United States and Imperial Germany saw this as a potential opportunity to expand their holdings in the Pacific through gunboat diplomacy.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] In order to be ready should such an opportunity arise, both nations had dispatched squadrons to the town to investigate the situation and act accordingly.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] A British ship was also present, ostensibly to observe the actions of the other nations during the Samoan upheavals.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] Increasing signs of the impending disaster were visible during the days that preceded the cyclone of March 15.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] March was the cyclone season in this area.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] Just three years earlier, Apia had been hit by a cyclone about which the local people told the captains of the anchored ships.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] The weather was beginning to change, and the atmospheric pressure was beginning to fall.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] The captains were experienced Pacific seamen, as were many members of their crews.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] Everyone saw the approaching signs of impending disaster.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] Everyone knew that the only chance of riding out the 100 mph (160 km/h) winds was to take to the open sea.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] Apia is an exposed harbour, unprotected by high ground or an enclosing reef.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] The northern part of the harbour is open to the Pacific.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] It is possible for the winds and the waves to sweep through the area, and to drive onto the reefs at the Southern end, or to toss up the beach any shipping which remained in the bay.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] No officers made a move, even though each officer of the various navies was well aware of the necessary procedures in the face of such a threat.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] This has been attributed to jingoism or national pride.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] No man in the harbour was willing to admit in front of the navies of other nations that he was afraid of the elements.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] The merchant ships that accompanied them were not allowed to move either.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] Thirteen ships, and some larger vessels, were left at anchor close to one another in the Apia harbour.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] The result was catastrophic when the cyclone made its landfall.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] The local people had taken themselves to safety well before the storm struck.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] The ships that were in the bay only began to evacuate at the very last minute.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] All the ships were crowded toward the entrance to the bay when the cyclone hit.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] Only HMS *Calliope* escaped, making less than one knot against the oncoming wind and sea.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] She dragged herself to the open sea, despite being less than six feet from a reef at one point.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] She was able to ride out the ensuing winds easily once she was out to sea.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] Her survival is attributed to her size (2,227 tons), and her more powerful and modern engines, built only five years earlier, as compared to the ten or twenty years for many of the other ships.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] Chaos reigned in the harbour for the other ships.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] USS *Trenton* was tossed against the beach in the afternoon, dragged back into the sea and wrecked on a reef at 10 p.m. that evening, although the majority of her crew survived unhurt and were able to participate in the ensuing rescue operation.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] USS *Vandalia* was smashed into the same reef in the early afternoon, and her surviving crew spent a miserable day and night clinging to her rigging before being rescued, by which time 43 of her complement had drowned.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] USS *Nipsic* was thrown high on the beach with eight of her crew missing or dead and her internal systems totally wrecked.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] She would however later be refloated and eventually reconstructed in Hawaii.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] The German ships fared much worse: SMS *Olga* came off best, thrown high onto the beach where she was wrecked but many of her crew survived, escaping onto higher ground.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] SMS *Adler* and SMS *Eber* were less fortunate, because they were caught at the harbour mouth by the initial blow and were bodily picked up and smashed together.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] *Eber* sank in deep water, while *Adler* came to rest on her side, on the reef.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] In total, 96 men from their crews drowned in the storm, and both ships were totally destroyed.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] All six of the merchant ships remaining in the harbour were wrecked, and the death toll was well over 200 sailors from several nationalities.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] The incident is often cited as a clear example of the dangers of putting national pride before necessity, especially in the face of natural disaster.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] The incident did not blunt the Pacific ambitions of any of the imperial powers involved in the disaster.
[src:samoa/1889-apia-cyclone] However, the Germans and British continued to make territorial gains amongst the Samoan islands and New Guinea, whilst the United States focused on the Philippines and Micronesia, although more care was taken to respect the weather phenomena of the Pacific from this point on.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] The **1991 Rugby World Cup** (French: *Coupe du monde de rugby 1991*) was the second edition of the Rugby World Cup, and was jointly hosted by England, Scotland, Wales, Ireland and France: at the time, the five European countries who participated in the Five Nations Championship.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] This was the first Rugby World Cup to be staged in the northern hemisphere, with England the hosts of the final.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] Also for the first time, qualifying competitions were introduced as the number of entrants had increased, from 16 nations four years earlier, to 33 countries.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] The eight quarter-finalists from 1987 qualified automatically with the remaining eight spots contested through qualifiers by 25 countries.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] This resulted in only one new side qualifying for the tournament, Western Samoa replacing Tonga.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] The same 16-team pool/knock-out format was used with just minor changes to the points system.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] South Africa was again not included because of sanctions imposed on the country by the International Rugby Board (IRB), due to the government's apartheid policies.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] The pool stages produced a major upset when Western Samoa, who were making their debut in the tournament, defeated the 1987 semi-finalists Wales 16–13 in Cardiff.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] Along with the other results in the group, this led to the elimination of Wales, who finished third in Pool 3.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] Also notable in pool play was that Canada finished second in their pool to qualify for the quarter-finals, which remains their best performance in the World Cup.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] Fiji, as quarter-finalists four years earlier, had expected to occupy that position, but after the upset loss to Canada and a hammering by France, they lost even their final match against the unfancied Romanian team.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] Earlier, the opening match had pitted the holders New Zealand against the hosts England: New Zealand overturned a narrow half-time deficit to win the match and the pool, both teams qualifying for the quarter-finals with easy victories in their other matches.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] Scotland beat Ireland to top their pool, again both teams qualifying.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] In the quarter-finals, neither Canada nor Western Samoa proved a match for New Zealand or Scotland, respectively.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] Meanwhile, England knocked out 1987 finalist France in a bruising encounter.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] Australia pipped Ireland 19–18 in a thrilling match at Lansdowne Road, with a last-gasp try from fly-half Michael Lynagh coming after the Irish took an unexpected 18–15 lead.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] The semi-finals produced two tight matches: England overcame Scotland 9–6, a late drop goal deciding a tryless match in a torrential downpour at Murrayfield Stadium, and Australia defeated the defending champions New Zealand 16–6 at Lansdowne Road.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] The final was played at Twickenham Stadium in London, and saw Australia win 12–6 against England, with a first-half try from prop Tony Daly.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] The following 16 teams, shown by region, qualified for the 1991 Rugby World Cup.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] Of the 16 teams, eight of those places were automatically filled by quarter-finalists from the 1987 World Cup and did not have to play any qualification matches.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] 25 nations competed in a qualification process designed to fill the remaining eight spots, bringing the total participation to 33 nations.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] In the event, there was only one change from the 1987 tournament, with Western Samoa appearing in place of Tonga.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] As in the 1987 Rugby World Cup the 16 nations were divided into four pools of four nations, with each nation playing their other pool opponents once, every nation playing three times during the pool stages.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] Nations were awarded 2 points for a win, 1 for a draw and zero for a loss, the top two nations of every pool advanced to the quarter-finals.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] The runners-up of each pool faced the winners of a different pool in the quarter-finals.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] The winners moved on to the semi-finals, with the winners then moving onto the final, and the losers of the semi-finals contesting a third/fourth place play off.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] A total of 32 matches (24 in the pool stage and eight in the knock-out stage) were played throughout the tournament over 30 days from 3 October 1991 to 2 November 1991.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] The tournament's top point scorer was Ireland's Ralph Keyes, who scored 68 points.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] David Campese and Jean-Baptiste Lafond scored the most tries, six in total.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] The event was broadcast in the United Kingdom by ITV who took over the rights from the BBC.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] 13 million people in the United Kingdom watched the final.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] In Australia it was the second and the last (as of the 2023 tournament) Rugby World Cup to be broadcast on ABC television as, from 1995, the commercial networks 7, 9 and 10 would all take over the broadcast rights sometimes in partnership with pay and streaming broadcasters Fox and Stan.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] In New Zealand, it was broadcast by TVNZ.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] In France, it was broadcast by TF1 instead of France's traditional Rugby broadcasters Antenne2.
[src:samoa/1991-rugby-world-cup] ITV, TF1 and RTE were the host broadcasters broadcasting the pictures around the world as well to their own countries.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The **1995 Rugby World Cup** (Afrikaans: *Rugbywêreldbeker 1995*) was the third Rugby World Cup.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] It was hosted and won by South Africa, and was the first Rugby World Cup in which every match was held in one country.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The World Cup was the first major sporting event to take place in South Africa following the end of apartheid.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] It was also the first World Cup in which South Africa was allowed to compete; the International Rugby Football Board (IRFB, now World Rugby) had only readmitted South Africa to international rugby in 1992, following negotiations to end apartheid.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The World Cup was also the last major event of rugby union's amateur era; two months after the tournament, the IRFB opened the sport to professionalism.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] In the final, held at Ellis Park in Johannesburg on 24 June, South Africa defeated New Zealand 15–12, with Joel Stransky scoring a drop goal in extra time to win the match.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] Following South Africa's victory, Nelson Mandela, the President of South Africa, wearing a Springboks rugby shirt and cap, presented the Webb Ellis Cup to the South African captain François Pienaar.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The eight quarter-finalists from the 1991 Rugby World Cup all received automatic entry, as did South Africa, as hosts.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The remaining seven of the 16 positions available in the tournament were filled by regional qualifiers.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The qualifying tournaments were broken up into regional associations: Africa, the Americas, Asia, Europe and Oceania.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] Côte d'Ivoire qualified through Africa, Japan through Asia, Argentina through the Americas, Italy, Romania and Wales through Europe, Tonga through Oceania.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The 1995 tournament was the first Rugby World Cup to be hosted by just one country, and thus, all the venues are within the one country.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] South Africa were given the rights to host the tournament in 1993, after a meeting between the IRB and both the government led by F.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] W. de Klerk and the African National Congress.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] In total, nine stadiums were used for the World Cup, most being owned by local municipalities, and the majority of the venues were upgraded prior to the tournament.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] Six of the nine stadiums were South African Test grounds.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The four largest stadiums were used for the finals, with the final taking place at Johannesburg's Ellis Park.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] There were games originally scheduled to have been played in Brakpan, Germiston, Pietermaritzburg and Witbank, but these games were reallocated to other venues.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] This reduced the number of venues from 14 to 9.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The reasons cited for this change had to do with facilities for both the press and spectators, as well as the security.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The change in the itinerary occurred in January 1994.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] Further changes occurred in April, so that evening games were played at stadiums with good floodlighting.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] It is also thought that Potchefstroom was an original venue.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The tournament was contested by 16 nations using the same format that was used in 1987 and 1991 and in total 32 matches were played.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The competition began on 25 May, when the hosts South Africa defeated Australia 27–18 at Newlands in Cape Town.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The tournament culminated with the final between South Africa and the All Blacks at Ellis Park in Johannesburg on 24 June.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] In total, the tournament ran for thirty days.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The nations were broken up into four pools of four, with each pool consisting of two teams that were automatically qualified and two that went through the qualifying tournaments.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] Pool winners were drawn against opposite pool runners-up in the quarter-finals.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] For example, the winner of A faces the runner up of B, and the winner of B face the runner-up of A.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The whole finals stage adopts a knock-out format, and the winners of the quarter-finals advance to the semi-finals, where winner 1 faces winner 2, and winner 3 faces winner 4.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The winners advance to the final, and the losers contest a third/fourth place play-off two days before the final.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] A total of 32 matches (24 pool stage & 8 knock-out) were played throughout the tournament over 30 days from 25 May to 24 June 1995.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] Three minutes into the match between Ivory Coast and Tonga, the Ivorian winger Max Brito was crushed beneath several other players, leaving him paralysed below the neck.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The final was contested by New Zealand and hosts South Africa.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] Both nations finished undefeated at the top of their pools.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] South Africa defeated Western Samoa in the quarter-finals, and then France in the semi-finals to reach the final; New Zealand defeated Scotland in the quarter-finals, and England in the semi-finals, a game in which Jonah Lomu famously scored four tries for the All Blacks.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The final was played at Ellis Park in Johannesburg and refereed by Ed Morrison of England.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] To this point, New Zealand had led the tournament in production, outscoring their opponents 315–104, while South Africa had outscored their opponents 129–55.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The tight Springbok defence would keep the high scoring All Blacks in check – particularly Jonah Lomu and Marc Ellis, who had already scored a then World Cup record seven tries each in the tournament – with neither team scoring a try in the match.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] South Africa led 9–6 at half time, and New Zealand levelled the scores at 9–9 with a drop goal in the second half.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] Though Andrew Mehrtens almost kicked a late drop goal for the All Blacks, the score remained tied at full-time, forcing the game into extra time.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] Both teams scored penalty goals in the first half of extra time, but Joel Stransky then scored a drop goal to win the final for South Africa.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] An iconic moment occurred after the game when Nelson Mandela, wearing a Springbok rugby jersey and cap, presented the Webb Ellis Cup to South African captain François Pienaar.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The moment is thought by some to be one of the most famous finals of any sport.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The tournament's top point scorer was France's Thierry Lacroix, who scored 112 points.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] Marc Ellis and Jonah Lomu, both of New Zealand, scored the most tries, with seven each.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The event was broadcast in Australia by Network Ten and in the United Kingdom by ITV.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] The South African Mint issued a one-ounce gold proof "Protea" coin with a total mintage of 406 pieces to commemorate the event being hosted by South Africa.
[src:samoa/1995-rugby-world-cup] Mandela and Pienaar's involvement in the World Cup is the subject of the John Carlin book *Playing the Enemy: Nelson Mandela and the Game That Made a Nation*, its 2009 film adaptation *Invictus*, and the ESPN TV documentary *The 16th Man* in 2010.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] An ***ʻie tōga*** is a special finely woven mat that is an important item of cultural value in Samoa.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] They are commonly referred to in English as "fine mats" although they are never used as mats as they only have a purely cultural value. ʻIe tōga are valued by the quality of the weave and the softness and shine of the material.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] They are made by women and form an important part of their role, identity and skill in their community.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] ʻIe tōga have an unwoven fringe and a strip of red feathers.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] They are important in gift exchanges during cultural ceremonies and events including *matai* chief title bestowals, weddings and funerals.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] In this way, ʻie tōga are passed from family to family, sometimes for many years and are greatly valued.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] Historically, some ʻie tōga were so valuable they were given their own names.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] The process of making a fine ʻie tōga can take months of work and have been known to take years.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] The completion of ʻie tōga can involve a public celebration and presentation with the women parading and displaying their fine mats for all to see.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] ʻIe tōga are never used as an actual floor mat in the western sense, functioning only as an item of cultural value.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] They are considered the most precious item in ceremony and gift exchanges, important in *faʻa-Sāmoa*.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] They represent most of the traditional wealth of Samoan families.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] They are exchanged and presented at weddings and funerals, and at special occasions such as the blessing of a newly built **fale** (house) or the opening of a new church. ʻIe tōga are sometimes worn at special occasions, around the waist, similar to a *lavalava*.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] At funerals ʻie tōga are given to the family of the deceased and gifts of mats and food are given in return.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] These exchanges display a mutual respect that enforces family (*ʻaiga*) ties.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] The best quality of ʻie tōga are made from a variety of long leaved pandanus known as *lauʻie*.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] More common types of 'ie toga with a coarser weave are made from *laufala*, a variety of pandanus which has a darker green colour than the *lauʻie* plant.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] The pandanus are grown in village plantations.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] The long leaves are selected and cut from the plant and taken back to the village.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] The leaves are prepared by soaking in boiling water followed by drying and bleaching in the sun.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] Once dry, the leaves are rolled and tied into bundles in preparation for weaving.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] The long dried leaves are then slit into thin strips for weaving.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] In the 19th century, young women would start their own mats or complete ones started by older sisters.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] Today, it is more common for mats to be woven by a group of women working in a *fale lalaga* (weaving house).
[src:samoa/ie-toga] The decorative red feathers were originally from Samoan or Fijian collared lory birds, called "sega," but more modern examples use dyed chicken feathers.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] The word *tōga* is cognate to Māori: *taonga* “treasure, property” and Tongan: *tōʻonga* “custom, habit, conduct, behaviour, characteristic; rite, ceremony”.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] Native speakers habitually recognize the proper pronunciation, but given the commonly unaccented spelling "toga", it is common to see the term misspelled thus later associated with "Toga," the Samoan spelling of Tonga.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] Hence the inaccurate explanation that "ʻie tōga" means "Tongan mat." The actual translation of "tōga" is "treasured" or "valuable" and the term also refers collectively to prestige goods produced by women for ceremonial exchanges.
[src:samoa/ie-toga] The Tongan cognate of "ʻie tōga" is "kie tōʻonga," while " ʻoloa" and "koloa" are also cognates.
[src:samoa/page] The explicitly double-barred (Dollar sign with two vertical lines) sign is called *cifrão* in the Portuguese language.
[src:samoa/page] The sign is also used in several compound currency symbols, such as the Brazilian real (R$) and the United States dollar (US$): in local use, the nationality prefix is usually omitted.
[src:samoa/page] In countries that have other currency symbols, the US dollar is often assumed and the "US" prefix omitted.
[src:samoa/page] The one- and two-stroke versions are often considered mere stylistic (typeface) variants, although in some places and epochs one of them may have been specifically assigned, by law or custom, to a specific currency.
[src:samoa/page] The Unicode computer encoding standard defines a single code for both.
[src:samoa/page] In most English-speaking countries that use that symbol, it is placed to the left of the amount specified, e.g.
[src:samoa/page] The symbol appears in business correspondence in the 1770s from the West Indies referring to the Spanish American peso, also known as "Spanish dollar" or "piece of eight" in British America.
[src:samoa/page] The Spanish coins provided the model for the currency that the United States adopted in 1792, and for the larger coins of the new Spanish American republics, such as the Mexican peso, Argentine peso, Peruvian real, and Bolivian sol coins.
[src:samoa/page] With the Coinage Act of 1792, the United States Congress created the U.S. dollar, defining it to have "the value of a Spanish milled dollar as the same is now current" but a variety of foreign coins were deemed to be legal tender until the Coinage Act of 1857 ended this status.
[src:samoa/page] The earliest U.S. dollar coins did not have any dollar symbol.
[src:samoa/page] The first occurrence in print is claimed to be from 1790s, by a Philadelphia printer Archibald Binny, creator of the Monticello typeface.
[src:samoa/page] The $1 United States Note issued by the United States in 1869 included a large symbol consisting of a 'U' with the right bar overlapping an 'S' like a single-bar dollar sign, as well as a very small double-stroke dollar sign in the legal warning against forgery *see picture*.
[src:samoa/page] It is still uncertain, however, how the dollar sign came to represent the Spanish American peso.
[src:samoa/page] The numerous currencies called "dollar" use the dollar sign to express money amounts.
[src:samoa/page] The sign is also generally used for the many currencies called "peso" (except the Philippine peso, which uses the symbol "₱").
[src:samoa/page] Within a country the dollar/peso sign may be used alone.
[src:samoa/page] In other cases, and to avoid ambiguity in international usage, it is usually combined with other glyphs, e.g.
[src:samoa/page] Particularly in professional contexts, the unambiguous ISO 4217 three letter code (AUD, MXN, USD, etc.) is preferred.
[src:samoa/page] The exception is French-speaking Canada, where the dollar symbol usually appears after the number, the same as the spoken order, e.g., "5 $" for "*cinq dollars*".
[src:samoa/page] In Portugal, Brazil, and other parts of the Portuguese Empire, the two-stroke variant of the sign named ***cifrão*** (Portuguese pronunciation: [siˈfɾɐ̃w] ⓘ; plural *cifrões*) has been used as the thousands separator in the national currency, the real (plural "réis", abbreviated "Rs.").
[src:samoa/page] For instance, 123(Dollar sign with two vertical lines)500 would be equivalent to 123500 réis.
[src:samoa/page] This usage is attested in 1775, but may be older by a century or more.
[src:samoa/page] The cifrão is always written with two vertical lines like (Dollar sign with two vertical lines), and is the official sign of the Cape Verdean escudo (ISO 4217: CVE).
[src:samoa/page] In 1911, Portugal redefined the national currency as the escudo, worth 1000 réis, and divided into 100 *centavos*; but the *cifrão* continued to be used as the decimal separator, so that 123(Dollar sign with two vertical lines)50 meant 123.50 escudos or 123 escudos and 50 centavos.
[src:samoa/page] This usage ended in 2002 when the country switched to the euro.
[src:samoa/page] Cape Verde, a republic and former Portuguese colony, similarly switched from the real to their local escudo and centavos in 1914, and retains the *cifrão* usage as decimals separator as of 2021.
[src:samoa/page] Brazil retained the real and the *cifrão* as thousands separator until 1942, when it switched to the Brazilian cruzeiro, with comma as the decimals separator.
[src:samoa/page] The dollar sign, officially with one stroke but often rendered with two, was retained as part of the currency symbol "Cr$", so one would write Cr$13,50 for 13 cruzeiros and 50 centavos.
[src:samoa/page] The *cifrão* was formerly used by the Portuguese escudo (ISO: PTE) before its replacement by the euro and by the Portuguese Timor escudo (ISO: TPE) before its replacement by the Indonesian rupiah and the US dollar.
[src:samoa/page] In Portuguese and Cape Verdean usage, the *cifrão* is placed as a decimal point between the escudo and *centavo* values.
[src:samoa/page] The name originates in the Arabic *ṣifr* (‏صِفْر‎), meaning 'zero'.
[src:samoa/page] Outside the Portuguese cultural sphere, the South Vietnamese đồng before 1975 used a method similar to the *cifrão* to separate values of đồng from its decimal subunit *xu*.
[src:samoa/page] For example, 7(Dollar sign with two vertical lines)50 meant 7 đồng and 50 xu.
[src:samoa/page] In some places and at some times, the one- and two-stroke variants have been used in the same contexts to distinguish between the U.S. dollar and other local currency, such as the former Portuguese escudo.
[src:samoa/page] However, such usage is not standardized, and the Unicode specification considers the two versions as graphic variants of the same symbol—a typeface design choice.
[src:samoa/page] Computer and typewriter keyboards usually have a single key for that sign, and many character encodings (including ASCII and Unicode) reserve a single numeric code for it.
[src:samoa/page] Indeed, dollar signs in the same digital document may be rendered with one or two strokes, if different computer fonts are used, but the underlying codepoint U+0024 (ASCII 3610) remains unchanged.
[src:samoa/page] When a specific variant is not mandated by law or custom, the choice is usually a matter of expediency or aesthetic preference.
[src:samoa/page] Both versions were used in the US in the 18th century.
[src:samoa/page] (An 1861 Civil War-era advertisement depicts the two-stroked symbol as a snake.) The two-stroke version seems to be generally less popular today, though used in some "old-style" fonts like Baskerville.
[src:samoa/page] Because of its use in early American computer applications such as business accounting, the dollar sign is almost universally present in computer character sets, and thus has been appropriated for many purposes unrelated to money in programming languages and command languages.
[src:samoa/page] The dollar sign "$" has ASCII and Unicode code point U+0024 (in Unicode's Latin-1 block inherited from ASCII).
[src:samoa/page] There are no separate encodings for one- and two-line variants.
[src:samoa/page] The choice is typeface-dependent; they are allographs.
[src:samoa/page] However, there are three other code points that originate from other East Asian standards: the Taiwanese small form variant, the CJK fullwidth form, and the Japanese emoji.
[src:samoa/page] The glyphs for these code points are typically larger or smaller than the primary code point, but the difference is mostly aesthetic or typographic, and the meanings of the symbols are the same.
[src:samoa/page] However, for usage as the special character in various computing applications (see following sections), U+0024 is typically the only code that is recognized.
[src:samoa/page] Support for the two-line variant varies.
[src:samoa/page] As of 2019, the Unicode standard considers the distinction between one- and two-bar dollar signs a stylistic distinction between fonts, and has no separate code point for the *cifrão*.
[src:samoa/page] The symbol is not in the October 2019 "pipeline", though it has been requested formally.
[src:samoa/page] In LaTeX, with the textcomp package installed, the *cifrão* ((Dollar sign with two vertical lines)) can be input using the command `\textdollaroldstyle`.
[src:samoa/page] However, because of font substitution and the lack of a dedicated code point, the author of an electronic document who uses one of these fonts intending to represent a *cifrão* cannot be sure that every reader will see a double-bar glyph rather than the single barred version.
[src:samoa/page] Because of the continued lack of support in Unicode, a single bar dollar sign is frequently employed in its place even for official purposes.
[src:samoa/page] Where there is any risk of misunderstanding, the ISO 4217 three-letter acronym is used.
[src:samoa/page] The character U+3326 ㌦ SQUARE DORU is a squared word version of ドル (*doru* "dollar", in Japanese).
[src:samoa/page] The character U+5F17 弗 CJK UNIFIED IDEOGRAPH-5F17 has been formerly repurposed as a symbol for dollars in Japan because of its visual similarity.
[src:samoa/page] The symbol is sometimes used derisively, in place of the letter S, to indicate greed or excess money such as in "Micro$oft", "Di$ney", "Chel$ea" and "GW$"; or supposed overt Americanization as in "$ky".
[src:samoa/page] The dollar sign is also used intentionally to stylize names such as A$AP Rocky, Ke$ha, and Ty Dolla $ign or words such as ¥€$.
[src:samoa/page] In 1872, Ambrose Bierce referred to California governor Leland Stanford as $tealand Landford.
[src:samoa/page] In Scrabble notation, a dollar sign is placed after a word to indicate that it is valid according to the North American word lists, but not according to the British word lists.
[src:samoa/page] A dollar symbol is used as unit of reactivity for a nuclear reactor, 0 $ being the threshold of slow criticality, meaning a steady reaction rate, while 1 $ is the threshold of prompt criticality, which means a nuclear excursion or explosion.
[src:samoa/page] In the 1993 version of the Turkmen Latin alphabet $ was used as a transliteration of the Cyrillic letter Ш, in 1999 was replaced by the letter Ş.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Lapita people discovered and settled the Samoan Islands around 3,500 years ago.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] They developed a Samoan language and Samoan cultural identity.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Because of the Samoans' seafaring skills, pre-20th-century European explorers referred to the entire island group, including American Samoa, as the "Navigator Islands".
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The country became a colony of the German Empire in 1899 after the Tripartite Convention, and was known as German Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] German administration ended in August 1914 after New Zealand troops bloodlessly occupied the colony at the start of World War I.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] New Zealand officially gained control of the region as a League of Nations mandate in 1920, when it became the Territory of Western Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] After being converted into a United Nations Trust Territory in 1946, Western Samoa gained independence on 1 January 1962 and officially returned to its original pre-occupation name *Samoa* on 4 July 1997.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoa is a unitary parliamentary democracy with 11 administrative divisions.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] It was admitted to the United Nations on 15 December 1976 and the country is also a member of the Commonwealth of Nations and the Pacific Islands Forum.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The island's defence is responsible to the New Zealand Defence Force.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoa may come from Samoan: *Sāmoa*, lit.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] 'holy centre', uniting a compound of Samoan: *sā*, lit.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The name is alternatively derived from a local chieftain named Samoa or an indigenous word meaning 'place of the chicken'.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] From independence in 1962, the country was officially known as the *Independent State of Western Samoa*, commonly known as *Western Samoa*.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] From 4 July 1997, the country changed its name to *Samoa*, drawing protests from nearby American Samoa, although the former name remains in use, especially their .ws top-domain.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The islands of Samoa were formed from the Miocene period.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] For the past 2 million years, the Samoan archipelago has experienced activity related to volcanic hotspots.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoa was discovered and settled by the Lapita people (Austronesian people who spoke Oceanic languages), who travelled from Island Melanesia.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The earliest human remains found in Samoa are dated to between roughly 2,900 and 3,500 years ago.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The remains were discovered at a Lapita site at Mulifanua, and the scientists' findings were published in 1974.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Samoans' origins have been studied in modern times through scientific research on Polynesian genetics, linguistics, and anthropology.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] However, while this research is ongoing, a number of theories have been proposed in the meantime.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] One theory is that the original Samoans were Austronesians who arrived during a final period of eastward expansion of the Lapita peoples out of Southeast Asia and Melanesia between 2,500 and 1,500 BCE.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Intimate sociocultural and genetic ties were maintained between Samoa, Fiji, and Tonga, and the archaeological record supports oral tradition and native genealogies that indicate interisland voyaging and intermarriage among precolonial Samoans, Fijians, and Tongans.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Notable figures in Samoan history included the Tui Manu'a line, Queen Salamasina, King Fonoti and the four *tama a ʻāiga*: Malietoa, Tupua Tamasese, Mataʻafa, and Tuimalealiʻifano.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Nafanua was a famous woman warrior who was deified in ancient Samoan religion and whose patronage was highly sought after by successive Samoan rulers.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Today, all of Samoa is united under its two principal royal families: the Sā Malietoa of the ancient Malietoa lineage that defeated the Tongans in the 13th century; and the Sā Tupua, Queen Salamasina's descendants and heirs who ruled Samoa in the centuries that followed her reign.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Within these two principal lineages are the four highest titles of Samoa – the elder titles of Malietoa and Tupua Tamasese of antiquity and the newer Mataʻafa and Tuimalealiʻifano titles, which rose to prominence in 19th-century wars that preceded the colonial period.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] These four titles form the apex of the Samoan matai system as it stands today.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Contact with Europeans began in the early 18th century.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Jacob Roggeveen, a Dutchman, was the first known non-Polynesian to sight the Samoan islands in 1722.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] This visit was followed by French explorer Louis Antoine de Bougainville, who named them the Navigator Islands in 1768.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Contact was limited before the 1830s, which is when British missionaries of the London Missionary Society, whalers, and traders began arriving.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Visits by American trading and whaling vessels were important in the early economic development of Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Salem brig *Roscoe* (Captain Benjamin Vanderford), in October 1821, was the first American trading vessel known to have called, and the *Maro* (Captain Richard Macy) of Nantucket, in 1824, was the first recorded United States whaler at Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The whalers came for fresh drinking water, firewood, provisions and, later, for recruiting local men to serve as crewmen on their ships.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The last recorded whaler visitor was the *Governor Morton* in 1870.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Christian missionary work in Samoa began in 1830 when John Williams of the London Missionary Society arrived in Sapapali'i from the Cook Islands and Tahiti.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Even as they descended into ever greater interclan warfare, what most alarmed Stevenson was the Samoans' economic innocence.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] He had "seen these judgments of God" in Hawaii, where abandoned native churches stood like tombstones "over a grave, in the midst of the white men's sugar fields".
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Germans, in particular, began to show great commercial interest in the Samoan Islands, especially on the island of Upolu, where German firms monopolised copra and cocoa bean processing.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The United States laid its own claim, based on commercial shipping interests in Pearl Harbor in Hawaii and Pago Pago Bay in eastern Samoa, and forced alliances, most conspicuously on the islands of Tutuila and Manu'a, which became American Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Britain also sent troops to protect British business enterprise, harbour rights, and consulate office.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] This was followed by an eight-year civil war, during which each of the three powers supplied arms, training and in some cases combat troops to the warring Samoan parties.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Samoan crisis came to a critical juncture in March 1889 when all three colonial contenders sent warships into Apia harbour, and a larger-scale war seemed imminent.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] A massive storm on 15 March 1889 damaged or destroyed the warships, ending the military conflict.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Second Samoan Civil War reached a head in 1898 when Germany, the United Kingdom, and the United States were locked in dispute over who should control the Samoan Islands.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Siege of Apia occurred in March 1899.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoan forces loyal to Prince Tanu were besieged by a larger force of Samoan rebels loyal to Mataʻafa Iosefo.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Supporting Prince Tanu were landing parties from four British and American warships.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] After several days of fighting, the Samoan rebels were finally defeated.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] American and British warships shelled Apia on 15 March 1899, including the USS *Philadelphia*.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Germany, the United Kingdom and the United States quickly resolved to end the hostilities and divided the island chain at the Tripartite Convention of 1899, signed at Washington on 2 December 1899 with ratifications exchanged on 16 February 1900.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The eastern island-group became a territory of the United States (the Tutuila Islands in 1900 and officially Manu'a in 1904) and was known as American Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The western islands, by far the greater landmass, became German Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The United Kingdom had vacated all claims in Samoa and in return received (1) termination of German rights in Tonga, (2) all of the Solomon Islands south of Bougainville, and (3) territorial alignments in West Africa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The German Empire governed the western part of the Samoan archipelago from 1900 to 1914.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Wilhelm Solf was appointed the colony's first governor.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In 1908, when the non-violent Mau a Pule resistance movement arose, Solf did not hesitate to banish the Mau leader Lauaki Namulau'ulu Mamoe to Saipan in the German Northern Mariana Islands.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The German colonial administration governed on the principle that "there was only one government in the islands." Thus, there was no Samoan *Tupu* (king), nor an *alii sili* (similar to a governor), but two *Fautua* (advisors) were appointed by the colonial government.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] *Tumua* and *Pule* (traditional governments of Upolu and Savai'i) were for a time silent; all decisions on matters affecting lands and titles were under the control of the colonial Governor.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] From the end of World War I until 1962, New Zealand controlled Western Samoa as a Class C Mandate under trusteeship through the League of Nations, then through the United Nations.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Between 1919 and 1962, Samoa was administered by the Department of External Affairs, a government department which had been specially created to oversee New Zealand's Island Territories and Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In 1943, this department was renamed the Department of Island Territories after a separate Department of External Affairs was created to conduct New Zealand's foreign affairs.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] During the period of New Zealand control, their administrators were responsible for two major incidents.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In the first incident, approximately one fifth of the Samoan population died in the influenza epidemic of 1918–1919.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In 1918, during the final stages of World War I, the Spanish flu had taken its toll, spreading rapidly from country to country.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] On Samoa, there had been no epidemic of pneumonic influenza in Western Samoa before the arrival of the SS *Talune* from Auckland on 7 November 1918.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The NZ administration allowed the ship to berth in breach of quarantine; within seven days of this ship's arrival, influenza became epidemic in Upolu and then spread rapidly throughout the rest of the territory.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoa suffered the most of all Pacific islands, with 90% of the population infected; 30% of adult men, 22% of adult women and 10% of children died.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The cause of the epidemic was confirmed in 1919 by a Royal Commission of Inquiry into the Epidemic concluded that there had been no epidemic of pneumonic influenza in Western Samoa before the arrival of the *Talune* from Auckland on 7 November 1918.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The pandemic undermined Samoan confidence in New Zealand's administrative capacity and competence.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Some Samoans asked that the rule of the islands be transferred to the Americans or the British.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The second major incident arose out of an initially peaceful protest by the Mau (which translates as "strongly held opinion"), a non-violent popular pro-independence movement which had its beginnings in the early 1900s on Savai'i, led by Lauaki Namulauulu Mamoe, an orator chief deposed by Solf.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In 1909, Lauaki was exiled to Saipan and died en route back to Samoa in 1915.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] By 1918, Western Samoa had a population of some 38,000 Samoans and 1,500 Europeans.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] However, native Samoans greatly resented New Zealand's colonial rule, and blamed inflation and the catastrophic 1918 flu epidemic on its misrule.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] By the late 1920s the resistance movement against colonial rule had gathered widespread support.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] One of the Mau leaders was Olaf Frederick Nelson, a half Samoan and half Swedish merchant.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Nelson was eventually exiled during the late 1920s and early 1930s, but he continued to assist the organisation financially and politically.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In accordance with the Mau's non-violent philosophy, the newly elected leader, High Chief Tupua Tamasese Lealofi, led his fellow uniformed Mau in a peaceful demonstration in downtown Apia on 28 December 1929.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The New Zealand police attempted to arrest one of the leaders in the demonstration.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] When he resisted, a struggle developed between the police and the Mau.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The officers began to fire randomly into the crowd and used a Lewis machine gun, mounted in preparation for the demonstration, to disperse the demonstrators.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Mau leader and paramount chief Tupua Tamasese Lealofi III was shot from behind and killed while trying to bring calm and order to the Mau demonstrators.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Ten others died that day and approximately 50 were injured by gunshot wounds and police batons.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] That day would come to be known in Samoa as Black Saturday.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] On 13 January 1930, the New Zealand authorities banned the organisation.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] As many as 1500 Mau men took to the bush, pursued by an armed force of 150 marines and seamen from the light cruiser HMS *Dunedin*, and 50 military police.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] They were supported by a seaplane flown by Flight Lieutenant Sidney Wallingford of the New Zealand Permanent Air Force.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Villages were raided, often at night and with fixed bayonets.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In March, through the mediation of local Europeans and missionaries, Mau leaders met New Zealand's Minister of Defence and agreed to disperse.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Supporters of the Mau continued to be arrested, so women came to the fore rallying supporters and staging demonstrations.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The political stalemate was broken following the victory of the Labour Party in New Zealand's 1935 general election.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] A 'goodwill mission' to Apia in June 1936 recognised the Mau as a legitimate political organisation, and Olaf Nelson was allowed to return from exile.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In September 1936, Samoans exercised for the first time the right to elect the members of the advisory *Fono of Faipule*, with representatives of the Mau movement winning 31 of the 39 seats.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] After repeated efforts by the Samoan independence movement, the New Zealand Western Samoa Act of 24 November 1961 terminated the Trusteeship Agreement and granted the country independence as the *Independent State of Western Samoa*, effective 1 January 1962.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Western Samoa, the first small-island country in the Pacific to become independent, signed a Treaty of Friendship with New Zealand later in 1962.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Western Samoa joined the Commonwealth of Nations on 28 August 1970.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] While independence was achieved at the beginning of January, Samoa annually celebrates 1 June as its independence day.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] At the time of independence, Fiamē Mataʻafa Faumuina Mulinuʻu II, one of the four highest-ranking paramount chiefs in the country, became Samoa's first prime minister.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Another paramount chief, Tuiaana Tuimalealiʻifano Suatipatipa II, was admitted to the Council of Deputies; the remaining two – Tupua Tamasese Meaʻole and Malietoa Tanumafili II – became joint heads of state for life.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] On 15 December 1976, Western Samoa was admitted to the United Nations as the 147th member state.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] It asked to be referred to in the United Nations as the *Independent State of Samoa*.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Travel writer Paul Theroux noted marked differences between the societies in Western Samoa and American Samoa in 1992.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Western Samoa had signed the UN Convention on the Law of the Sea on 28 September 1984, so indicating its intentions, and ratified it on 14 August 1995, making the island nation a party in efforts to manage marine resources and protect its vast regional ocean territory.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The convention entered into force for Western Samoa on 13 September 1995.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] On 4 July 1997 the government amended the constitution to change the name of the country from *Western Samoa* to *Samoa*, the name it had been called by in the United Nations since it joined.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] American Samoa protested against the name change, asserting that it diminished its own identity.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In 2002, New Zealand prime minister Helen Clark formally apologised for New Zealand's role in the Spanish influenza outbreak in 1918 that killed over a quarter of Samoa's population and for the Black Saturday killings in 1929.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] On 7 September 2009, the government changed the rule of the road from right to left, in common with most other Commonwealth countries – most notably countries in the region such as Australia and New Zealand, home to large numbers of Samoans.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] This made Samoa the first country in the 21st century to switch to driving on the left.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] At the end of December 2011, Samoa changed its time zone offset from UTC−11 to UTC+13, effectively jumping forward by one day, omitting Friday, 30 December from the local calendar.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] This also changed the shape of the International Date Line, moving it to the east of the territory.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] This change aimed to help the nation boost its economy in doing business with Australia and New Zealand.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Before this change, Samoa was 21 hours behind Sydney, but the change means it is now three hours ahead.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The previous time zone, implemented on 4 July 1892, operated in line with American traders based in California.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In October 2021, Samoa ceased daylight saving time.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In 2017, Samoa signed the UN treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In June 2017, Parliament amended Article 1 of the Samoan Constitution to make Christianity the state religion.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In May 2021, Fiamē Naomi Mataʻafa became Samoa's first female prime minister.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Mataʻafa's FAST party narrowly won the election, ending the rule of long-term Prime Minister Tuilaʻepa Saʻilele Malielegaoi of the Human Rights Protection Party (HRPP), although the constitutional crisis complicated and delayed this.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] On 24 May 2021, she was sworn in as the new prime minister, though it was not until July that the Supreme Court ruled that her swearing-in was legal, thus ending the constitutional crisis and bringing an end to Tuilaʻepa's 22-year premiership.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The FAST party's success in the 2021 election and subsequent court rulings also ended nearly four decades of HRPP rule.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In 2025, after Mataʻafa dismissed FAST leader and agriculture minister Laʻauli Leuatea Schmidt over corruption charges, she was in turn expelled from FAST.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] After FAST, led by Schmidt, won the ensuing snap election, he replaced Mataʻafa as prime minister.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The 1960 constitution, which formally came into force with independence from New Zealand in 1962, builds on the British pattern of parliamentary democracy, modified to take account of Samoan customs.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The national modern Government of Samoa is referred to as the *Malo*.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The head of state of Samoa is known as the *O le Ao o le Malo* in Samoan, and since its establishment only paramount chiefs have held the office.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The current head of state is Tuimalealiʻifano Vaʻaletoʻa Sualauvi II, who was elected by the legislature in 2017 and again in 2022.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Legislative Assembly or *Fono* is the unicameral legislature, consisting of 51 members serving five year terms.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Forty-nine are *matai* title-holders elected from territorial districts by Samoans; the other two are chosen by non-Samoans with no chiefly affiliation on separate electoral rolls.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] At least ten per cent of the MPs must be women.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Universal suffrage was adopted in 1990, but only chiefs (*matai*) may stand for election to the Samoan seats.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] There are more than 25,000 matais in the country, about five per cent of whom are women.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The prime minister, chosen by a majority in the assembly, is appointed by the head of state to form a government.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The prime minister's choices for the 12 cabinet positions are appointed by the head of state, subject to the continuing confidence of the legislative assembly.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Since 2025, Laʻauli Leuatea Schmidt has served as prime minister, while Auapaʻau Mulipola Aloitafua has been speaker of the Legislative Assembly.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Prominent women in Samoan politics include the late Laʻulu Fetauimalemau Mataʻafa (1928–2007) from Lotofaga constituency, the wife of Samoa's first prime minister.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Their daughter Fiamē Naomi Mataʻafa is a *matai* and a long-serving senior member of cabinet, who was elected Prime Minister in 2021.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Other women in politics include Samoan scholar and eminent professor Aiono Fanaafi Le Tagaloa, orator-chief Matatumua Maimoana and Safuneituʻuga Paʻaga Neri (former Minister of Communication and Technology).
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The judicial system incorporates English common law and local customs.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Supreme Court of Samoa is the court of highest jurisdiction.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Chief Justice of Samoa is appointed by the head of state upon the recommendation of the prime minister.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoa comprises eleven *itūmālō* (political districts).
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] These are the traditional eleven districts which predate European arrival.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Each district has its own constitutional foundation (*faʻavae*) based on the traditional order of title precedence found in each district's *faalupega* (traditional salutations).
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The capital village of each district administers and coordinates the affairs of the district and confers each district's paramount title, amongst other responsibilities.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] 1 including the faipule district of Siumu 2 including islands Manono, Apolima and Nuʻulopa 3 including the Aleipata Islands and Nuʻusafeʻe Island 4 smaller parts also on Upolu (Salamumu, incl.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Major areas of concern include the under-representation of women, domestic violence and poor prison conditions.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In June 2017, an Act was passed changing the country's constitution to include a reference to the Trinity.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] As amended, Article 1 of the Samoan Constitution states that "Samoa is a Christian nation founded on God the Father, the Son and the Holy Spirit".
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoa has no formal defence structure or regular armed forces.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] It has informal defence ties with New Zealand, which is required to consider any request for assistance from Samoa under the bilateral Treaty of Friendship of 1962.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Officers of the national police force, the Samoa Police Service, are regularly unarmed, but may be armed in exceptional circumstances with ministerial approval.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] As of 2022 there are between 900 and 1,100 police officers in Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoa lies south of the equator, about halfway between Hawaii and New Zealand, in the Polynesian region of the Pacific Ocean.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The total land area is 2,842 km2 (1,097 sq mi), consisting of the two large islands of Upolu and Savaiʻi (which together account for 99% of the total land area) and eight small islets.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The main island of Upolu is home to nearly three-quarters of Samoa's population, and to the capital city, Apia.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Samoan islands result geologically from volcanism, originating with the Samoa hotspot, which probably results from a mantle plume.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] While all of the islands have volcanic origins, only Savaiʻi, the westernmost island in Samoa, remains volcanically active, with the most recent eruptions at Mount Matavanu (1905–1911), Mata o le Afi (1902) and Mauga Afi (1725).
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The highest point in Samoa is Mount Silisili, at 1,858 m (6,096 ft).
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Saleaula lava fields situated on the central north coast of Savaiʻi result from the Mount Matavanu eruptions, which left 50 km2 (19 sq mi) of solidified lava.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Savaiʻi is the largest of the Samoan islands and the sixth-largest Polynesian island (after New Zealand's North, South and Stewart Islands and the Hawaiian islands of Hawaiʻi and Maui).
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The population of Savaiʻi is roughly 42 thousand people.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The average annual temperature of 26.5 °C (79.7 °F) and a main rainy season from November to April, although heavy rain may fall in any month.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoa forms part of the Samoan tropical moist forests ecoregion.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Since human habitation began, about 80% of the lowland rainforests have disappeared.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] However, with recent reforestation, about 60.4% or about 171,000 ha of Samoa is forested, of which 32,000 ha is planted forest.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Within the ecoregion about 28% of plants and 84% of land birds are endemic.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In June 2025, Samoa legally adopted the *Samoa Marine Spatial Plan*, a marine spatial planning framework that applies across Samoa's exclusive economic zone and uses ocean zoning to designate fully protected marine protected areas alongside zones intended for managed use.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The adoption included nine new fully protected marine protected areas covering 36,000 km2 (14,000 sq mi).
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Stakeholder consultations during the marine spatial planning process included partners such as Conservation International Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The United Nations has classified Samoa as an economically developing country since 2014.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] As of 2017 Samoa's gross domestic product in purchasing-power parity was estimated at $1.13 billion U.S. dollars, ranking the country 204th in the world.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The services sector accounted for 66% of GDP, followed by industry and agriculture at 23.6% and 10.4% respectively.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] For the same year, the Samoan labour force was estimated at 50,700.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Central Bank of Samoa issues and regulates Samoa's currency, the Samoan tālā.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The economy of Samoa has traditionally depended on agriculture and fishing at the local level.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In modern times, development aid, private family remittances from overseas, and agricultural exports have become key factors in the nation's economy.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Agriculture employs two-thirds of the labour force and furnishes 90% of exports, featuring coconut cream, coconut oil, noni (juice of the *nonu* fruit, as it is known in Samoan), and copra.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Sixty percent of Samoa's electricity comes from renewable hydro, solar, and wind sources, with the remainder produced by diesel generators.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Electric Power Corporation set a goal of 100% renewable energy by 2021.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In 2024 about 200,000 tourists visited the country.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] As of 2024 tourism makes up around 20% of Samoa's GDP, a decrease from 24.5% in 2019.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The sector is volatile, affected by pandemics such as the 2019 measles outbreak and COVID-19 and by natural disasters such as cyclones and the 2009 tsunami.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The biggest sources of international tourists are New Zealand, Australia and the United States.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In 2019, 38% of international arrivals were holidaymakers and 37% were visiting friends and family.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The peak season is from June to September during the drier Samoan winter, with another peak during December and January, coinciding with the summer school holiday break in New Zealand and Australia, when Samoans living overseas return to visit their families for Christmas.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoa is not as important a destination for cruise ships as some other Pacific Islands, but the Samoan government sees potential in expanding this sector of the tourism market.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoa markets itself internationally as 'Beautiful Samoa.' and promotes key attractions that include diving and snorkeling and unique features such as blowholes, lava fields and the To Sua ocean trench, a sinkhole and swimming hole.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] A 2013 report stated that the most popular activities for holidaymakers to Samoa are swimming or visiting beaches, relaxing, visiting cafes and restaurants, shopping and sightseeing.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The most popular attractions for holidaymakers were Lalomanu and Saleapaga beaches, To Sua Trench, Piula Cave Pool, Papaseea sliding rocks, Saleaula lava fields and Robert Louis Stevenson’s villa and grave.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In the period before German colonisation (from the late 19th century), Samoa produced mostly copra.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] German merchants and settlers were active in introducing large-scale plantation operations and in developing new industries, notably cocoa beans and rubber, relying on imported labourers from China and Melanesia.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] When the value of natural rubber fell drastically, about the end of World War I in 1918, the New Zealand government encouraged the production of bananas, for which there is a large market in New Zealand.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Because of variations in altitude, Samoa can cultivate a large range of tropical and subtropical crops.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Land is not generally available to outside interests.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Of the total land area of 2,934 km2 (725,000 acres), about 24.4% is in permanent crops and another 21.2% is arable.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] About 4.4% is Western Samoan Trust Estates Corporation (WSTEC).
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The staple products of Samoa are copra (dried coconut meat), cocoa beans (for chocolate), rubber, and bananas.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The annual production of both bananas and copra has been in the range of 13,000–15,000 tonnes (14,000–17,000 tons).
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] If the coconut rhinoceros beetle in Samoa were eradicated, Samoa could produce in excess of 40,000 tonnes (44,000 tons) of copra.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoan cocoa beans are of very high quality and are used in fine New Zealand chocolates.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Coffee grows well, but production has been uneven.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Other agricultural industries have proven less successful.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Sugarcane production was originally established by Germans in the early 20th century.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Old train tracks for transporting cane can be seen at some plantations east of Apia.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Pineapples grow well in Samoa, but have not moved beyond local consumption to become a major export.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoa's transportation infrastructure effectively connects its two main islands, Upolu and Savai'i, and facilitates travel to and from neighbouring regions.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Faleolo International Airport, located about 25 miles (40 kilometres) west of the capital Apia on Upolu Island, serves as Samoa's primary gateway for international flights.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The airport is managed by the Airports Authority and handles flights from various international carriers.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Samoa Shipping Corporation, established in 1974, operates regular ferry services between Upolu and Savai'i islands.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The main ferry route connects Mulifanua Wharf on Upolu with Salelologa Wharf on Savai'i, with a crossing time of approximately 60 to 90 minutes.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Ferries operate daily, providing both passenger and vehicle transport services.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The corporation also offers services to neighbouring territories, including American Samoa and Tokelau.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Public transportation within Samoa primarily consists of buses and taxis.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Buses are a popular mode of travel, with terminals located in Apia behind the Fugalei Food Market and in Savalalo next to the Fish Market.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] On Savai'i, bus terminals are situated at the market and main wharf in Salelologa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Fares are generally affordable, with the most one should expect to pay being SAT$12 per person.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Taxis are readily available and can be hired for both short trips and day-long excursions.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Renting a scooter is another option, offering flexibility to explore at one's own pace; however, wearing helmets is mandatory.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoa's road network consists mainly of paved highways connecting key towns and villages on both Upolu and Savai'i islands.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Driving is on the left-hand side of the road, a practice adopted in 2009 to align with neighbouring countries.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The roads are generally well-maintained, facilitating efficient travel across the islands.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The main port in Apia serves as the primary hub for international shipping, handling containerised cargo and fuel shipments.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The port also accommodates ferries traveling to American Samoa and other Pacific islands.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Additional ports, such as those in Salelologa on Savai'i, support inter-island ferry services and local maritime activities.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] While less common, some visitors and locals opt for cycling or walking, especially in rural areas.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] However, due to limited infrastructure for non-motorised transport, these modes are less prevalent for long-distance travel.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoa reported a population of 194,320 in its 2016 census.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] This number increased to 205,557 in its 2021 Census.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] About three-quarters of the population live on the main island of Upolu.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] A measles outbreak began in October 2019.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] By the time the outbreak subsided in early January, the number of deaths reached 83 (0.31 per 1,000, based on a population of 201,316) and over 4,460 cases (2.2% of the population) of measles in Samoa, mainly children under four years old, and 10 reported cases in Fiji.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The population is 96% Samoans, 2% dual Samoan New Zealanders and 1.9% other, according to a 2011 estimate in the CIA World Factbook.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoan (*Gagana Fa'asāmoa*) and English are the official languages.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Including second-language speakers, there are more speakers of Samoan than English in Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoan Sign Language is also commonly used among the deaf population of Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] To emphasise the importance of full inclusion with sign language, elementary Samoan Sign Language was taught to members of the Samoa Police Service, Red Cross Society, and public during the 2017 International Week of the Deaf.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Since 2017, Article 1 of the Samoan Constitution states that "Samoa is a Christian nation founded of God the Father, the Son and the Holy Spirit".
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] In addition, Samoa hosts the seventh (of the nine current) Baháʼí Houses of Worship in the world.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Completed in 1984 and dedicated by Malietoa Tanumafili II, a convert to the Baháʼí Faith, it is located in Tiapapata, 8 km (5.0 mi) from Apia.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Samoan government provides eight years of primary and secondary education that is tuition-free and is compulsory through age 16.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Samoa's main post-secondary educational institution is the National University of Samoa, established in 1984.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The country is also home to several branches of the multi-national University of the South Pacific and the Oceania University of Medicine.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] Education in Samoa has proved to be effective as a 2012 UNESCO report stated that 99 percent of Samoan adults are literate.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] The Human Rights Measurement Initiative (HRMI) finds that Samoa is fulfilling only 88.0% of what it should be fulfilling for the right to education based on the country's level of income.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] HRMI breaks down the right to education by looking at the rights to both primary education and secondary education.
[src:samoa/samoa-p01] While taking into consideration Samoa's income level, the nation is achieving 97.7% of what should be possible based on its resources (income) for primary education but only 78.3% for secondary education.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Faʻa Sāmoa, or the traditional Samoan way, remains a strong force in Samoan life and politics.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] As one of the oldest Polynesian cultures, the fa'a Samoa developed over a period of 3,000 years, withstanding centuries of European influence to maintain its historical customs, social and political systems, and language.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Cultural customs such as the Samoa 'ava ceremony are significant and solemn rituals at important occasions including the bestowal of *matai* chiefly titles.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Items of great cultural value include the finely woven *'ie toga*.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Samoan mythology includes many gods with creation stories and figures of legend such as Tagaloa and the goddess of war Nafanua, the daughter of Saveasi'uleo, ruler of the spirit realm Pulotu.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Other legends include the well known story of Sina and the Eel which explains the origins of the first coconut tree.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Some Samoans are spiritual and religious, and have subtly adapted the dominant religion of Christianity to 'fit in' with fa'a Samoa and vice versa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Ancient beliefs continue to co-exist side by side with Christianity, particularly in regard to the traditional customs and rituals of fa'a Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] The Samoan culture is centred on the principle of vāfealoa'i, the relationships between people.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] These relationships are based on respect, or fa'aaloalo.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] When Christianity was introduced in Samoa, most Samoan people converted.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Currently 98% of the population identify themselves as Christian.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Some Samoans live a communal way of life, participating in activities collectively.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Examples of this are the traditional Samoan *fale* (houses) which are open with no walls, using blinds made of coconut palm fronds during the night or bad weather.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] The Samoan *siva* dance has unique gentle movements of the body in time to music and tells a story, although the Samoan male dances can be more snappy.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] The *sasa* is also a traditional dance where rows of dancers perform rapid synchronised movements in time to the rhythm of wooden drums *(pate)* or rolled mats.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Another dance performed by males is called the *fa'ataupati* or the slap dance, creating rhythmic sounds by slapping different parts of the body.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] This is believed to have been derived from slapping insects on the body.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] The form and construction of traditional architecture of Samoa was a specialised skill by *Tufuga fai fale* that was also linked to other cultural artforms.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] As with other Polynesian cultures (Hawaiian, Tahitian and Māori) with significant and unique tattoos, Samoans have two gender-specific and culturally significant tattoos.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] For males, it is called the Pe'a and consists of intricate and geometrical patterns tattooed that cover areas from the knees up towards the ribs.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] A male who possesses such a tatau is called a soga'imiti.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] A Samoan girl or *teine* is given a malu, which covers the area from just below her knees to her upper thighs.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Albert Wendt is a significant Samoan writer whose novels and stories tell the Samoan experience.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] In 1989, his novel *Flying Fox in a Freedom Tree* was made into a feature film in New Zealand, directed by Martyn Sanderson.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Another novel *Sons for the Return Home* had also been made into a feature film in 1979, directed by Paul Maunder.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] The late John Kneubuhl, born in American Samoa, was an accomplished playwright and screenwriter and writer.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] His play *Think of Garden* premiered in Auckland in 1993 a year after his death, it was directed by Nathaniel Lees, is set in 1929 and is about Samoa's struggle for independence.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Sia Figiel won the 1997 Commonwealth Writers' Prize for fiction in the south-east Asia/South Pacific region with her novel "Where We Once Belonged".
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Momoe Malietoa Von Reiche is an internationally recognised poet and artist.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Her first book of poetry *Wild Dogs Under My Skirt* was published by Victoria University Press in 2004.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Dan Taulapapa McMullin is an artist and writer.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Other Samoan poets and writers include Sapa'u Ruperake Petaia, Eti Sa'aga and Savea Sano Malifa, the editor of the Samoa Observer.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] In music, popular local bands include The Five Stars, Penina o Tiafau and Punialava'a.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] The Yandall Sisters' cover of the song *Sweet Inspiration* reached number one on the New Zealand charts in 1974.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] King Kapisi was the first hip hop artist to receive the prestigious New Zealand APRA Silver Scroll Award in 1999 for his song *Reverse Resistance*.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] The music video for *Reverse Resistance* was filmed in Savai'i at his villages.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Other successful Samoan hip hop artists include rapper Scribe, Dei Hamo, Savage and Tha Feelstyle whose music video *Suamalie* was filmed in Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Lemi Ponifasio is a director and choreographer who is prominent internationally with his dance Company MAU.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Neil Ieremia's company Black Grace has also received international acclaim with tours to Europe and New York.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Hip hop has had a significant impact on Samoan culture.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] According to Katerina Martina Teaiwa, PhD from the University of Hawaii at Manoa, "Hip hop culture in particular is popular amongst Samoan youth." As in many other countries, hip hop music is popular.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Marilyn Kohlhase ran a Pacific focused gallery called *Okaioceanikart* from 2007 to 2013.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Other important Samoan contemporary artists include Andy Leleisi'uao, and Raymond Sagapolutele.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Urale's short film *O Tamaiti* won the prestigious Best Short Film at the Venice Film Festival in 1996.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Her first feature film *Apron Strings* opened the 2008 NZ International Film Festival.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] The feature film *Siones Wedding*, co-written by Oscar Kightley, was financially successful following premieres in Auckland and Apia.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] The 2011 film The Orator was the first ever fully Samoan film, shot in Samoa in the Samoan language with a Samoan cast telling a uniquely Samoan story.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Written and directed by Tusi Tamasese, it received much critical acclaim and attention at film festivals throughout the world.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] The main sports played in Samoa are rugby union, Samoan cricket and netball.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Rugby union is the national football code of Samoa.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] In Samoan villages, volleyball is also popular.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Rugby union is the national sport in Samoa and the national team, nicknamed the Manu Samoa, is consistently competitive against teams from vastly more populous nations.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Samoa has competed at every Rugby World Cup since 1991, and made the quarter finals in 1991, 1995 and the second round of the 1999 World Cup.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] At the 2003 world cup, Manu Samoa came close to beating eventual world champions, England.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Samoa also played in the Pacific Nations Cup and the Pacific Tri-Nations.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] The sport is governed by the Samoa Rugby Football Union, who are members of the Pacific Islands Rugby Alliance, and thus, also contribute to the international Pacific Islanders rugby union team.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] At club level, there is the National Provincial Championship and Pacific Rugby Cup.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] They also took home the cup at Wellington and the Hong Kong Rugby Sevens in 2007—for which the Prime Minister of Samoa, also chairman of the national rugby union, Tuila’epa Sa’ilele Malielegaoi, declared a national holiday.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] They were also the IRB World Sevens Series Champions in 2010 capping a year of achievement for the Samoans, following wins in the US, Australia, Hong Kong and Scotland Sevens tournaments.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Prominent Samoan players include Pat Lam and Brian Lima.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] In addition, many Samoans have played for or are playing for New Zealand.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] The national rugby league team reached the quarter finals of the 2013 Rugby League World Cup, the team comprising players from the NRL and Super League plus domestic players.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Other noteworthy players from NZ and Australia have represented the Samoan National team.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] The 2011 domestic Samoan rugby league competition contained 10 teams with plans to expand to 12 in 2012.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Samoa reached the final of the 2021 Rugby League World Cup to face Australia.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] Samoans have been very visible in boxing, kickboxing, wrestling, and sumo; some Samoan sumo wrestlers, most famously Musashimaru and Konishiki, have reached the highest rank of *Ozeki* and *yokozuna*.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] American football is occasionally played in Samoa, reflecting its wide popularity in American Samoa, where the sport is played under high school sanction.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] About 30 ethnic Samoans, many from American Samoa, currently play in the National Football League.
[src:samoa/samoa-p02] A 2002 article from *ESPN* estimated that a Samoan male (either an American Samoan or a Samoan living in the mainland United States) is 40 times more likely to play in the NFL than a non-Samoan American.
[src:samoa/ws] The .ws domain is an abbreviation for ***W**estern **S**amoa*, which was the nation's official name in the 1970s when two-letter country codes were standardized.
[src:samoa/ws] Although there are no geographic restrictions on registration of most second-level .ws domains, **.org.ws**, **.gov.ws**, and **.edu.ws** registration is restricted.
[src:samoa/ws] The .ws country code has been marketed as a domain hack, with the ws purportedly standing for "world site", website or web service, providing a "global" Internet presence to registrants, as it supports all internationalized domain names.
[src:samoa/ws] A popular use for the domain is for news organizations for URL shortening purposes, mainly suffixed as "(organization name)ne.ws".
[src:samoa/ws] Google Search treats the .ws ccTLD as a generic top-level domain (gTLD).
[src:samoa/ws] The registrar operates a sliding scale of prices depending on each domain's brevity.
[src:samoa/ws] Domains with four characters or more are competitively priced while three-, two-, and single-character domains have their own pricing tiers, quickly scaling into thousands of United States dollars.
[src:samoa/ws] Prior to March 14, 2008, .ws domains were not allowed to be transferred from one domain registrar to another.
[src:samoa/ws] In 2016, .ws gained popularity as one of the first domain name registries to offer emoji domains.
[src:samoa/ws] As of 2018, there are approximately 25,000 emoji domains registered on .ws.
